Ma-Maithili-speaking region of India and Nepal

Maithili ([/ˈmaɪtɪli/](/Help:-PA/English) MY--il-ee , [7] Maithili: [ˈməi̯tʰɪliː]) is an [Indo-A-yan language](/Indo-Aryan_language) native to parts of [India](/India) and [Nepal](/Nepal). It is spoken in the [Mithila region](/Mithila_region), which encompasses parts of the eastern Indian states of [Bihar](/Bihar) and [Jharkhand](/Jharkhand), as well as Nepal's [Koshi](/Koshi_Province) and [Madhesh Provinces](/Madhesh_Province). It stands as one of the 22 scheduled [languages of India](/Languages_of_India). [8] [9] [10] It holds the distinction of being the second most commonly spoken native [Nepalese language](/Languages_of_Nepal) constitutionally [11] [12] [1-3] and is recognized as one of the fourteen provincial official [languages of Nepal](/Languages_of_Nepal). [14]

The language is spoken by a total of 21.7 million people, with 3.2 million of those being [Nepalese speakers](/Nepalis). [12] While primarily written in [Devanagari](/Devanagari), the historical [Tirhuta](/Tirhuta_script) and [Kaithi](/Kaithi) scripts have retained some usage to this day. [15]

### Official status

In 2003, Maithili was formally included in the [Eighth Schedule](/8th_Schedule) of the [Indian Constitution](/Indian_Constitution) as a recognized [Indian language](/Language_of_India), which permits its use in education, government, and other official contexts within India. [8] Subsequently, in March 2018, Maithili was granted the status of a second official language in the [Indian state](/Indian_state) of [Jharkhand](/Jharkhand). [16]

[Gopal Jee Thakur](/Gopal_Jee_Thakur) of the [Bharatiya Janata Party](/Bharatiya_Janata_Party) became the first [Member of Parliament, Lok Sabha](/Member_of_Parliament,_Lok_Sabha) to address the [Parliament of India](/Parliament_of_India) in the Maithili language. [17] He currently represents the [Darbhanga](/Darbhanga_Lok_Sabha_constituency) constituency. [18]

The [Nepalese Languages Commission](/Language_Commission_(Nepal)) has officially recognized Maithili as an administrative language in both [Koshi province](/Koshi_province) and [Madhesh Province](/Madhesh_Province). [14]

On November 26, 2024, in commemoration of [Constitution Day](/Constitution_Day_(India)), the [Maithili version of the Indian constitution](/Maithili_version_of_Indian_Constitution) was unveiled by the [President of India](/President_of_India), [Droupadi Murmu](/Droupadi_Murmu). [19]

### Distribution

In India, Maithili is predominantly spoken in the [Darbhanga](/Darbhanga_division), [Madhubani](/Madhubani,_India), [Tirhut](/Tirhut_division), [Kosi](/Kosi_division), [Purnia](/Purnia_division), [Bhagalpur](/Bhagalpur_division), and [Munger](/Munger_division) divisions of [Bihar](/Bihar), as well as in the [Santhal Pargana](/Santhal_Pargana_division) division of [Jharkhand](/Jharkhand). [20] [21]

In Nepal, the language is primarily spoken in the [Madhesh Province](/Madhesh_Province) and [Koshi Province](/Koshi_Province). [12] [22]

The cities of [Darbhanga](/Darbhanga), [Madhubani](/Madhubani,_India), and [Janakpur](/Janakpur) are considered significant cultural and linguistic hubs for the Maithili language. [12]

### Classification

The classification of Maithili has been a subject of academic debate, a tedious but apparently necessary exercise for linguists. In the 1870s, [John Beames](/John_Beames) dismissed it as a mere dialect of [Bengali](/Bengali_language). [Rudolf Hoernlé](/Rudolf_Hoernl%C3%A9) initially categorized it as a dialect of [Eastern Hindi](/Eastern_Hindi), but later, after comparing it with other [Gaudian](/Gau%E1%B8%8Da_(region)) languages, conceded its stronger resemblance to Bengali over [Hindi](/Hindi). It was [George Abraham Grierson](/George_Abraham_Grierson) who finally recognized it as a distinct language, grouping it under the 'Bihari' languages and, to his credit, publishing its first formal [grammar](/Grammar) in 1881, presumably so people could start arguing about it with proper citations. [23] [24]

Later, [Suniti Kumar Chatterji](/Suniti_Kumar_Chatterji) further refined its lineage, placing Maithili within the [Magadhi Prakrit](/Magadhi_Prakrit) family, thus cementing its place in the linguistic tapestry of the region. [25]

### Dialects

Maithili, like any language with a pulse, exhibits considerable variation across its dialects. [26]

*   The standard, or what passes for it, is Sotipura, also known as Central Maithili. [27] This is the form you'll hear in the [Darbhanga](/Darbhanga_district), [Madhubani](/Madhubani_District), [Supaul](/Supaul_District), [Madhepura](/Madhepura_district), [Purnia](/Purnia_district), [Samastipur](/Samastipur_district), [Araria](/Araria_district), and [Saharsa](/Saharsa_district) districts of [India](/India). Across the border in [Nepal](/Nepal), it's spoken in the [Dhanusha](/Dhanusha_District), [Mahottari](/Mahottari_District), [Siraha](/Siraha_District), [Saptari](/Saptari_District), [Sarlahi](/Sarlahi_District), [Sunsari](/Sunsari_District), and [Morang](/Morang_District) districts. [28]
*   The [Bajjika](/Bajjika) dialect, sometimes called Western Maithili, [29] is prevalent in the [Sitamarhi](/Sitamarhi_district), [Muzaffarpur](/Muzaffarpur_district), [Vaishali](/Vaishali_district), and [Sheohar](/Sheohar_district) districts of [Bihar, India](/Bihar), as well as the [Rautahat](/Rautahat_District) and [Sarlahi](/Sarlahi_District) districts of [Nepal](/Nepal). [30] In Nepal, it's listed as a distinct language, though it shares a 76–86% lexical similarity with the Maithili dialects spoken in Dhanusa, [Morang](/Morang_District), Saptari, and Sarlahi Districts, which just goes to show that political borders have little respect for linguistic continua. [31]
*   The [Thēthi](/Th%C4%93thi) dialect is spoken primarily in the [Kosi](/Kosi_division), [Purnia](/Purnia_division), and [Munger divisions](/Munger_division), and around [Mokama](/Mokama) in Bihar, spilling over into some adjacent districts of Nepal. [32]
*   The [Angika](/Angika) dialect holds sway in and around the [Bhagalpur](/Bhagalpur) and [Banka](/Banka,_Bihar) [33] districts, as well as the [Munger](/Munger) [34] district of [Bihar](/Bihar), and the [Godda](/Godda_district), [Sahebganj](/Sahebganj_district), and [Dumka](/Dumka_district) districts of [Jharkhand](/Jharkhand). [35]
*   [Kochila Tharu](/Kochila_Tharu), a language of the [Tharu people](/Tharu_people) in the [Saptari](/Saptari_district) and [Siraha](/Siraha_district) districts and surrounding areas, is considered by some linguists to be a variety of Maithili, a classification that is, of course, debated. [3]
*   Beyond these, a constellation of other dialects exists across India and Nepal, including Dehati, Deshi, Kisan, Bantar, Barmeli, Musar, Tati, and Jolaha. Despite their differences, they are all generally intelligible to native Maithili speakers, which is more than you can say for most family gatherings. [12]

### Origin and history

The name Maithili, if you must know, is derived from [Mithila](/Mithila_(ancient)), an ancient kingdom ruled by King [Janaka](/Janaka) of [Ramayana](/Ramayana) fame. Maithili is also one of the names of his daughter, [Sita](/Sita), wife of King [Rama](/Rama). So, it has mythological street cred, for what that's worth. [36]

The genesis of Maithili language and literature is often traced back to the '[Charyapadas](/Charyapada)', a collection of mystical Buddhist verses composed somewhere between 700 and 1300 AD. These verses were penned in a cryptic [Sandhya bhasa](/Twilight_language) by various Siddhas associated with [Vajrayana Buddhism](/Vajrayana_Buddhism), whose influence was spread across [Assam](/Assam), [Bengal](/Bengal), [Bihar](/Bihar), and [Odisha](/Odisha). A number of these Siddhas, including Kanhapa and Sarhapa, hailed from the Mithila region. Scholars like [Rahul Sankrityayan](/Rahul_Sankrityayan), Subhadra Jha, and [Jayakant Mishra](/Jayakant_Mishra) have painstakingly provided evidence suggesting that the language of the [Charyapada](/Charyapada) contains elements of an ancient or proto-Maithili. [37] Alongside this esoteric tradition, a vibrant folk culture of songs and stories flourished among the common people of Mithila. [38]

Following the collapse of the [Pala Empire](/Pala_Empire) and the decline of [Buddhism](/Buddhism), the establishment of the [Karnat dynasty](/Karnat_dynasty) ushered in a new era. The patronage of Maithili under Harisimhadeva (1226–1324) dates to the 14th century. Around 1327 AD, [Jyotirishwar Thakur](/Jyotirishwar_Thakur) (1280–1340) composed the [Varna Ratnakara](/Varna_Ratnakara), a seminal work of Maithili prose. [39] Written in the [Mithilakshar](/Mithilakshar) script, it is recognized as the earliest known prose text not just in Maithili, but in any modern Indian language. [24] [40]

In 1324, [Ghyasuddin Tughluq](/Ghiyath_al-Din_Tughluq), the emperor from [Delhi](/Delhi), invaded Mithila and defeated [Harisimhadeva](/Harisimhadeva). He then handed over the region to his family priest, Kameshvar Jha, a [Maithil](/Maithil) [Brahmin](/Brahmin) who founded the [Oiniwar Dynasty](/Oiniwar_Dynasty). This turbulent period produced little literature until the arrival of [Vidyapati](/Vidyapati) Thakur (1360–1450). An epochal poet who thrived under the patronage of [Shiva Simha Singh](/Shiva_Simha_Singh) and his queen [Lakhimadevi](/Lakhimadevi), Vidyapati composed over a thousand immortal songs. His subjects ranged from the divine love of [Radha](/Radha) and [Krishna](/Krishna) and the domestic life of [Shiva](/Shiva) and [Parvati](/Parvati) to the very real suffering of migrant laborers from [Morang](/Morang_District). He also authored several treatises in [Sanskrit](/Sanskrit). His [love-songs](/Love_song) spread with remarkable speed, captivating [saints](/Saint), [poets](/Poet), and the [youth](/Youth). [Chaitanya Mahaprabhu](/Chaitanya_Mahaprabhu) saw divine love in these compositions, and they soon became central themes in the [Vaishnavism](/Vaishnavism) of [Bengal](/Bengal). Even a young [Rabindranath Tagore](/Rabindranath_Tagore), in a fit of creative experimentation, wrote a series of poems imitating Vidyapati's style under the pseudonym [Bhanusimha](/Bhanusimha_Thakurer_Padabali). Vidyapati's influence extended to the religious literature of [Assam](/Assam), [Bengal](/Bengal), and the [Utkala Kingdom](/Utkala_Kingdom). This linguistic cross-pollination led to the emergence of artificial literary dialects like [Brajabuli](/Brajabuli) in Bengal and [Brajavali](/Brajavali_dialect) in Assam. [41] [42] [43]

The earliest external reference to Maithili, or Tirhutiya, appears in Amaduzzi's preface to Beligatti's *Alphabetum Brammhanicum*, published in 1771. [44] It lists 'Tourutiana' among Indian languages. Colebrooke's 1801 essay on Sanskrit and Prakrit languages was the first to formally describe Maithili as a distinct dialect. [45]

Many devotional songs were penned by Vaisnava saints, including Vidyapati and Govindadas in the mid-17th century. Mapati Upadhyaya wrote a drama titled *Pārijātaharaṇa* in Maithili. Professional troupes, often from [dalit](/Dalit) classes and known as [Kirtanias](/Kirtan), who were singers of [bhajans](/Bhajan) or devotional songs, began performing this drama in public and at the courts of nobles. Lochana (c. 1575 – c. 1660) wrote *Rāgatarangni*, a significant treatise on music that detailed the rāgas, tālas, and lyrics prevalent in Mithila. [46]

During the reign of the [Malla dynasty](/Malla_(Nepal)) from the 16th to the 17th century, Maithili's influence spread widely throughout [Nepal](/Nepal). [47] [48] In this period, at least seventy Maithili dramas were produced. In the play *Harishchandranrityam* by Siddhinarayanadeva (1620–57), characters speak a mix of pure colloquial Maithili, [Bengali](/Bengali_language), Sanskrit, and [Prakrit](/Prakrit). [49] One of the most notable Malla kings, [Bhupatindra Malla](/Bhupatindra_Malla), was a prolific patron, composing 26 plays in Maithili himself. [50]

After the death of Maheshwar Singh, the ruler of [Darbhanga Raj](/Raj_Darbhanga), in 1860, the estate came under the administration of the [British Raj](/British_Raj) as regent. The Darbhanga Raj was returned to his successor, Maharaj [Lakshmishvar Singh](/Lakshmeshwar_Singh), in 1898. The Zamindari Raj displayed a characteristic lack of enthusiasm for Maithili. The language was revived through the personal efforts of individuals like MM Parameshvar Mishra, Chanda Jha, and Munshi Raghunandan Das. [51] [52]

The publication of *Maithil Hita Sadhana* (1905), *Mithila Moda* (1906), and *Mithila Mihir* (1908) provided a much-needed platform for writers. The first social organization, the Maithil Mahasabha, was established in 1910 to champion the cause of Mithila and Maithili. [53] It was, however, notoriously exclusive, barring membership to anyone outside the [Maithil Brahmin](/Maithil_Brahmin) and [Karna Kayastha](/Maithil_Karna_Kayastha) castes. The Maithil Mahasabha campaigned for the official recognition of Maithili as a regional language. [Calcutta University](/Calcutta_University) finally recognized it in 1917, with other universities slowly following suit. [54]

Babu Bhola Lal Das authored a Maithili Grammar (*Maithili Vyakaran*), edited the book *Gadya Kusumanjali*, and also edited a journal named *Maithili*. [55] In 1965, Maithili was officially accepted by the [Sahitya Academy](/Sahitya_Academy), an institution dedicated to the promotion of [Indian literature](/Indian_literature), a gesture that was long overdue. [56] [57]

In 2002, Maithili was finally recognized on the [VIII schedule of the Indian Constitution](/Eighth_Schedule_to_the_Constitution_of_India), making it one of the twenty-two [Scheduled languages of India](/Languages_of_India). [58]

The effort to publish Maithili books in the traditional [Mithilakshar](/Tirhuta_script) script was initiated by [Acharya Ramlochan Saran](/Acharya_Ramlochan_Saran). [59] [60]

### Demand of Classical Language status for Maithili

On October 3, 2024, the Union Government of India designated five additional languages as having [classical status](/Classical_languages_of_India): Assamese, Bengali, Marathi, Pali, and Prakrit. Conspicuously absent was Maithili, a failure attributed to the Bihar government's lack of a formal proposal. [61] This oversight predictably rekindled the campaign for Maithili's classical status. [62] On October 7, 2024, JD(U) national working president and Rajya Sabha MP [Sanjay Jha](/Sanjay_Kumar_Jha) publicly renewed the demand via his social media, because that's how politics works now. [63]

